<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="240" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,533,1007]" pageId="1" pageNumber="240">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,316,602,625]" pageId="1" pageNumber="240">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Carapace subpentagonal or pyriform, slightly longer than wider, covered with long conical spines (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,250,1800,1822]" captionTargetBox="[226,1360,1062,1775]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[226,1360,1062,1776]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Paralomis spinosissima Birstein &amp; Vinogradov, 1972, male, cl 13.61 mm, dorsal view (MACN-In 39716)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/232857/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="240">
Fig. 
<number box="[151,164,637,660]" pageId="1" pageNumber="240" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
). Juveniles have mushroom shape tubercles, with spiniform setae surrounding at the apex. Gastric region with a prominent spine. Branchial regions with acute spines. Lateral and posterior surface with small spines. Rostrum acute trispinose, overreaching the ocular peduncle; paired dorsal spines divergent, directed obliquely upwards, slightly shorter than the central, with a small spine between them (
<figureCitation box="[686,749,741,764]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1504,1526]" captionTargetBox="[250,1331,185,1475]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[240,1347,175,1483]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. Paralomis spinosissima, male, cl 13.61 mm (MACN-In 39716). A, anterior part of the carapace, dorsal view; B, anterior part of the carapace, lateral view; C, right cheliped; D, right cheliped, dorsal view; E, third left walking leg. Scale bar = 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/232858/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="240">
Fig. 
<number box="[735,749,741,764]" pageId="1" pageNumber="240" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
A). Ocular peduncle with a longest dorsal spine overreaching the cornea; with scattered smaller spines along its length; some spines with several apical setae (
<figureCitation box="[1158,1223,776,799]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1504,1526]" captionTargetBox="[250,1331,185,1475]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[240,1347,175,1483]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. Paralomis spinosissima, male, cl 13.61 mm (MACN-In 39716). A, anterior part of the carapace, dorsal view; B, anterior part of the carapace, lateral view; C, right cheliped; D, right cheliped, dorsal view; E, third left walking leg. Scale bar = 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/232858/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="240">
Fig. 
<number box="[1209,1223,776,799]" pageId="1" pageNumber="240" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
A, B). Scaphocerite slender, armed with a long central acute spine, two lateral smaller spines and one short inner spine (
<figureCitation box="[1224,1290,810,833]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1504,1526]" captionTargetBox="[250,1331,185,1475]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[240,1347,175,1483]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. Paralomis spinosissima, male, cl 13.61 mm (MACN-In 39716). A, anterior part of the carapace, dorsal view; B, anterior part of the carapace, lateral view; C, right cheliped; D, right cheliped, dorsal view; E, third left walking leg. Scale bar = 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/232858/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="240">
Fig. 
<number box="[1275,1290,810,833]" pageId="1" pageNumber="240" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
B). Chelipeds and walking legs densely covered with long and acute spines; dorsal margin with prominent spines; ventral margin armed with blunt spines, in juveniles specimens have blunt tubercles with a tuft of long and rigid setae (
<figureCitation box="[1258,1321,880,903]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1504,1526]" captionTargetBox="[250,1331,185,1475]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[240,1347,175,1483]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. Paralomis spinosissima, male, cl 13.61 mm (MACN-In 39716). A, anterior part of the carapace, dorsal view; B, anterior part of the carapace, lateral view; C, right cheliped; D, right cheliped, dorsal view; E, third left walking leg. Scale bar = 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/232858/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="240">
Fig. 
<number box="[1307,1321,880,903]" pageId="1" pageNumber="240" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
C, D, E).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
